==English==

===Etymology===
c. 1387, {{inh|en|enm|pamphilet}}, {{m|enm|panflet|t=small, unbound treatise}}, from {{der|en|xno|Pamphilet}}, diminutive of {{der|en|fro|Pamphile}}, used as a popular shorthand for the 12th century {{der|en|la|-}} love poem {{m|la|{{w|Pamphilus de amore|Pamphilus (seu) de amore}}|t=Pamphilus (or) On Love}}, which was so widely circulated in pamphlets as to give name to the whole phenomenon; the eponym from {{der|en|grc|Πάμφιλος|lit=beloved by all}}, deriving from {{pre|grc|παν|φίλος|nocat=1}}. Further borrowed as {{w|Anglo-Latin literature|Anglo-Latin}} {{m|la|panflettus}}.

For the use of the diminutive of the author's name as shorthand for Latin titles in French cf. {{m|frm|Isopet|Ysopet/Esopet}} from {{m|fr|Ésope}}, {{m|frm|Catonet}} from {{m|fr|Caton}}, {{m|frm|Avionet}} from {{m|la|Avianus}}.

